WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:12.120
Hello and welcome to Imagine Belfast. I'm Alan Mabin and on this penultimate evening

00:12.120 --> 00:17.920
of the 2023 Festival, it's our Festival of Ideas and Politics. What better way, what

00:17.920 --> 00:23.640
better company could we have to spend it than with Noam Chomsky, renowned linguist, philosopher,

00:23.640 --> 00:28.200
political activist and public intellectual and over the years a great friend to this

00:28.200 --> 00:31.760
festival. Noam, you're very welcome back to Imagine Festival.

00:31.760 --> 00:36.320
Thank you very much. Pleased to be with you.

00:36.320 --> 00:42.840
I've been part of quite a few online conversations this week and one of the very common factors

00:42.840 --> 00:49.720
is that there have been stacks of books behind the people. Now tonight you have plants rather

00:49.720 --> 00:56.200
than books but in the past you might have had a good bookcase there. Do you fear that

00:56.200 --> 01:02.040
in the world of screens and so on that words on paper are starting to become less common

01:02.040 --> 01:04.680
by losing their value?

01:04.680 --> 01:12.120
Certainly and there are good measures of it. So there have been studies when going on for

01:12.120 --> 01:24.720
a long time. There have been studies of books that are assigned to young people in schools.

01:24.720 --> 01:35.040
Turns out that even 20, 30 years ago there was a tendency to assign to the high school

01:35.040 --> 01:41.880
students, 12th grade students that used books that used to be read in eighth grade. We get

01:41.880 --> 01:46.360
students coming into the university who don't know how to write an essay. They've never

01:46.360 --> 01:54.520
had that experience. Part of this is the effect of the so-called teaching to test movement

01:54.520 --> 02:02.280
of the last 20 years, Bush, Obama and so on. Part of it is just the decline in reading

02:02.280 --> 02:07.960
all together and it's getting worse. There was a study that just came out a couple days

02:07.960 --> 02:18.280
ago of the, I think it's called Generation Z, the people who were born after 1997, high

02:18.280 --> 02:26.120
school college students asking where do they get their so-called information? Almost none

02:26.120 --> 02:33.760
look at the newspapers, almost none look at television. They didn't stop looking at Facebook

02:33.760 --> 02:42.320
to old fashioned. They're getting their news from channels where kids are having fun dancing

02:42.320 --> 02:52.200
around. Of course, that's having an effect. The social media have other effects. They're

02:52.200 --> 03:01.080
tending to drive people into self-reinforcing bubbles. We're all subject to that. I am too.

03:01.080 --> 03:08.040
When I pick up and start looking at things in the morning, I don't look at Breitbart.

03:08.080 --> 03:16.000
I look at maybe Democracy Now or something like that and conversely, well, the media with all

03:16.000 --> 03:26.560
their limitations have a certain amount of range of discussion and debate limited, but some not

03:26.560 --> 03:32.760
the self-reinforcing bubbles and self-reinforcing is the crucial part. It means you don't get

03:32.760 --> 03:40.840
anything but enhancing your own beliefs and prejudices. Reading is declining along with it.

03:42.920 --> 03:50.040
When it comes to when you're working as an academic, there would be fewer of the journals

03:50.040 --> 03:55.880
that are available on paper, more of them are online, fewer books available on paper. Are you

03:55.920 --> 04:03.160
missing paper-based things? Do you soak in as much information when you're reading on a screen or

04:03.160 --> 04:12.520
have you got used to it? Well, there are plenty of fine books available, but the question is,

04:12.520 --> 04:20.960
do people access them? There's plenty of important information available on the screen. For example,

04:21.440 --> 04:28.240
I can sit in the United States, I can read the foreign press. You learn a lot from it. How many

04:28.240 --> 04:37.920
people do that? Virtually nobody. It's surprising if they even read the national press, let alone

04:39.120 --> 04:48.080
the foreign press. You learn a lot. Recently, I learned about a pretty incredible scandal,

04:48.800 --> 04:58.400
which is not reported here. This is called what aboutism? If you pardon it, I'll talk about the

04:58.400 --> 05:05.920
real world. I'm not allowed to talk about that. Take the invasion of Iraq. There were enormous

05:05.920 --> 05:13.200
atrocities. Some of the worst, most outlandish, outrageous atrocities were the destruction of

05:13.200 --> 05:23.200
Fallujah. Recently, a couple months ago, the US Navy just commissioned its latest assault vessel.

05:23.920 --> 05:32.400
It's called the USS Fallujah in commemoration of one of the most atrocious atrocities of the

05:32.400 --> 05:38.240
worst crime of the 20th century. I didn't learn about it here. I learned about it in Al Jazeera,

05:39.040 --> 05:45.440
where I could also read the reaction of the Iraqis to it, naturally outraged.

05:48.400 --> 05:56.320
That information is available in principle, but you have to be motivated, stimulated,

05:57.520 --> 06:02.640
educated enough to understand that you have to look at things that are available.

06:03.200 --> 06:14.400
That's very rare, unfortunately. If the press and the media are still acting

06:14.400 --> 06:20.880
as mediators between all that information out there and people who are kind of tuning into

06:20.880 --> 06:29.040
either mass read or mass watch stuff, does the media and the press need to do more

06:29.120 --> 06:35.840
to actually increase the range of stories that they tell, or is social media enough

06:35.840 --> 06:41.120
that it's up to each of us to find out that information? Because not everybody is bothered

06:41.120 --> 06:45.840
to wake up in the morning and even listen to the news. Never mind. Go and search it out.

06:48.000 --> 06:54.960
Well, just talk about myself. The first thing I do in the morning when I get up is read the New

06:54.960 --> 07:04.000
York Times and the Washington Post two national newspapers, two national newspapers. That's

07:04.000 --> 07:11.440
important. There used to be lots of newspapers, so there were local high-quality newspapers.

07:12.160 --> 07:18.880
I lived in Boston most of my life. Boston Globe was a pretty substantial paper, had some of the

07:18.880 --> 07:25.920
best reporting, not only domestically, but also internationally, had the best coverage in the

07:25.920 --> 07:34.400
country of the Central America Wars in the 1980s. Actually, the editor was personal friends. Some

07:34.400 --> 07:44.400
of the reporters were gone. Now it's wire service and local news. Same with all over the country,

07:44.400 --> 07:51.760
Detroit Free Press, San Francisco Chronicle, Los Angeles Times, Chicago Tribune,

07:52.880 --> 07:59.520
the newspapers have radically constricted. What happened is that the business model

08:00.480 --> 08:08.240
could not survive the internet. The business model for the media is basically advertising.

08:08.960 --> 08:17.600
So the media are businesses that sell a product, you and me, to other businesses. It's their

08:17.600 --> 08:25.280
central structure that collapsed with the shift of advertising to the internet. One major effect

08:25.280 --> 08:32.720
is radical reduction of the available information in the press. It's had the same effect on the

08:32.800 --> 08:39.120
major press as well. They've constricted. It takes me much less time to read the New York Times today

08:39.120 --> 08:48.640
than it did 30 or 40 years ago because it's constrained, limited. Well, all these are serious

08:48.640 --> 08:58.000
effects of basically the capitalist institutional structure, which imposes a certain constraint

08:58.000 --> 09:03.840
on the nature of media. Could be changed by public media. Actually, they've declined too,

09:04.720 --> 09:14.240
but it's not an issue in the United States because we don't have them. That's no BBC, no German

09:14.240 --> 09:21.760
national television. The reason for that is a difference between the United States and other

09:21.760 --> 09:28.000
state capitalist societies. The United States has a very powerful business class,

09:28.800 --> 09:37.280
class conscience, constantly fighting a savage class war. This showed up with the media, showed

09:37.280 --> 09:47.120
up with radio in the 1920s, early 30s. There were attempts to popular attempts, popular groups,

09:47.200 --> 09:54.080
political groups, church groups, others to try to create national media, public media,

09:54.080 --> 10:01.600
that would respond to interests of the general population was defeated by a corporate opinion

10:01.600 --> 10:07.200
to turn it into private media. Same thing happened with television 20 years later.

10:08.160 --> 10:17.120
A result in the United States is essentially no public media margin, even that is corporate funding.

10:19.440 --> 10:26.240
That's lost. You have to find other means to try to get out of the institutional factors

10:26.320 --> 10:36.960
based on particular forms of savage capitalism, state capitalism that are constraining the

10:37.760 --> 10:45.920
means of information available. Now, they are there. You can go to the internet and find out

10:45.920 --> 10:56.080
quite a lot. I just think that that's a special for a marginal part of the population, even among

10:56.080 --> 11:04.480
the educated classes, very few do it. While we're talking about the media, can we talk about Fox News?

11:05.120 --> 11:13.200
Can we talk about Dominion voting systems with their defamation case? There nearly seems to be

11:13.280 --> 11:18.560
more written about Rupert Murdoch who's going to get married again than there is written about the

11:18.560 --> 11:25.680
actual case and the arguments that are going on in court. Should we be surprised that actually

11:25.680 --> 11:31.520
that certainly over on this side of the Atlantic, it's getting reported but just a little.

11:32.640 --> 11:37.840
It's not a big story, whereas it could have big implications for Fox News. It could have big

11:37.840 --> 11:45.840
implications for your next presidential election. I doubt that it'll have much one effect. First

11:45.840 --> 11:52.160
of all, Fox News is not a news channel. It's an echo chamber for the far right.

11:53.840 --> 12:00.720
You're familiar with that in England. The Murdoch system is not interested in providing

12:00.720 --> 12:10.160
news to people. It's providing echo chambers for far right propaganda. Fox News is kind of

12:10.160 --> 12:17.920
interesting. I look at it sometimes just to see how wild and extremely far right can be. It's kind

12:17.920 --> 12:23.760
of amusing. Sometimes I actually tell you the truth. They're a little more open in some respects

12:23.840 --> 12:31.680
than the major media. For example, personal experience. I've had interviews and discussion

12:31.680 --> 12:43.280
on Fox News, not in the major media. That would be very, very rare. I suspect that this scandal,

12:43.280 --> 12:55.200
the court case, will blow over somehow and they'll have the same role in the coming period of

12:55.200 --> 13:04.720
political confrontations. Do you still value, even if you don't see it as a news channel,

13:04.720 --> 13:11.840
do you still value it as part of the plurality of outlets telling the same stories in different

13:11.840 --> 13:26.080
ways? Is it still valuable to have it there? Well, frankly, I don't see much value in having a

13:26.720 --> 13:32.320
pure propaganda channel. You live in Russia. Yes, that's what you have, but I don't think we need it.

13:32.880 --> 13:39.920
What we need is to strengthen, expand the actual media system. So, for example,

13:48.640 --> 13:56.160
there were serious and other ways of public support. There aren't technical means to do that.

13:56.720 --> 14:01.680
There are people actually working on it, like Robert Bobman Chesney,

14:04.720 --> 14:10.080
who is a scholar at the University of Illinois. I'm just trying to reconstruct

14:13.280 --> 14:22.160
significant local media system, also the level of national media. But the main point is, the main

14:22.160 --> 14:29.440
goal is educating people to recognize that there are things you have to understand about the world,

14:29.440 --> 14:36.400
and you're not going to find them from a limited, even a limited media system, certainly not from

14:36.400 --> 14:42.560
social media. Now, this goes back to questions about what's happening to the whole social order.

14:43.200 --> 14:50.240
Why aren't people getting together to look at these things? They used to. One reason is there

14:50.240 --> 15:00.480
used to be something called unions, labor unions. Labor unions were not just ways of raising wages.

15:01.440 --> 15:10.880
They were cultural educational institutions. Adult education was a core part of the union

15:10.880 --> 15:18.800
programs. Unions are places where people could get together, discuss, study, cultural events,

15:20.480 --> 15:27.280
Reagan and Thatcher or their advisors were very sensible when they launched the

15:27.840 --> 15:34.960
neoliberal assault against the population. First move, destroy the unions, the one way that people

15:34.960 --> 15:43.120
have to have to protect and defend themselves. That was very effective. New labor Clinton,

15:43.120 --> 15:49.920
they gave their own support to it. Now it's pretty much

15:51.520 --> 16:03.680
on the United States almost gone. Another modes of intercommunication, when people you get atomization,

16:04.320 --> 16:16.400
isolation, easy prey to demagogues of the Trump variety, to fake news organizations like the

16:16.400 --> 16:26.320
Murdoch media. People that don't have the means of self-defense that they had when they were

16:26.400 --> 16:34.320
organized, could interact with one another, mutual support, solidarity, common goals and so on.

16:35.040 --> 16:40.240
It's very interesting to see how powerful the efforts are to destroy this.

16:41.440 --> 16:49.920
Just saw a remarkable case in England with the Corbyn phenomenon. Corbyn broke with this

16:50.880 --> 17:01.840
long-term policy pursued by the Tory government and the Blair right new labor. What he did was

17:03.120 --> 17:10.640
a real crime. He tried to create a labor party that would be a participatory party

17:11.440 --> 17:18.240
and would respond to the needs and concerns of working people and the poor and it was very

17:18.320 --> 17:30.000
successful. 2017, they were under his influence when the biggest victory they had, as far back as

17:30.000 --> 17:38.880
you can imagine, the whole establishment came down on him like a ton of bricks from the right wing

17:38.880 --> 17:46.400
over to the Guardian and have this. We cannot have an authentic political party

17:48.720 --> 17:56.800
that will break with domination by a small elite committed to the rich and powerful.

17:58.640 --> 18:06.000
You know what happened? It was charges of total fakery about anti-Semitism. It was all exposed.

18:06.000 --> 18:12.400
You could read the extensive exposure and held to zero again, but even the Labor Party's own

18:13.200 --> 18:20.480
commission looking into it exposed it as a fraud. No effect. Now, this is too important. We cannot

18:20.480 --> 18:27.680
allow a development like that. That might lead to a functioning democratic society.

18:28.320 --> 18:35.040
We don't want that. This is a society which must be in the hands of the rich and the powerful.

18:36.960 --> 18:44.880
We are fighting a constant class war, no break from that. It's very striking. Something similar

18:44.880 --> 18:52.320
happened in the United States, less extreme, with the Democratic party, the Clintonite party

18:53.200 --> 19:00.880
moving along with the media to try to crush the Sanders phenomenon. It wasn't as extreme as in England,

19:01.680 --> 19:08.000
but it had the effect of pretty much marginalizing the popular forces.

19:10.160 --> 19:15.680
I suspect there are those who are members of the Labor Party in the UK who would dispute

19:16.880 --> 19:24.800
your conclusion, but it does point to a difficulty when a party wants to change quickly,

19:25.440 --> 19:32.080
when it wants to either go back to old values or new values. That seems a very difficult thing

19:32.080 --> 19:36.640
for them to achieve. Is that going to be difficult for the Republican party to achieve if it wants

19:37.280 --> 19:42.800
not to have Trump or if the Democrats want to reinvent? They don't seem terribly sure what

19:42.800 --> 19:48.160
their ideology is at the moment. They're searching in terms of their policies. They're not selling

19:48.160 --> 19:56.160
them well. I don't think that's the issue. It's very easy for a Republican to change. Let's take

19:56.160 --> 20:05.360
the Republican Party in the United States. 2008, the Republican candidate for president was John

20:05.360 --> 20:16.240
McCain. The most important issue in human affairs is the environmental crisis, which is going to

20:16.320 --> 20:21.520
destroy organized human life on earth. That's the most important issue in history.

20:22.240 --> 20:31.360
Well, 2008, the Republican Party did begin to move towards a small, limited climate program.

20:32.000 --> 20:43.840
Not much, but something. McCain had a climate most part of the platform,

20:43.920 --> 20:49.920
congressional Republicans were looking into things. The Koch brothers energy conglomerate,

20:49.920 --> 20:59.840
huge conglomerate, which had been working for years to try to ensure that there was no interference

20:59.840 --> 21:06.080
with their campaign to destroy organized human life on earth. When they, as soon as the Republican

21:06.080 --> 21:14.960
Party began to shift immediately, they launched an enormous juggernaut intimidation, bribery,

21:14.960 --> 21:23.360
threats, massive lobbying, asterisks, or asterisk organizations. The Republican Party turned on

21:23.360 --> 21:33.440
a dime. They all turned total denialism. It's very easy to change a party's direction if you have

21:33.440 --> 21:42.800
massive capital working for savage class war, plenty of other cases. So the issue is not

21:45.040 --> 21:52.400
difficulty of changing. The problem was the kind of change that Corbyn was trying to bring about,

21:53.280 --> 22:02.400
a change to a labor party that would be a participatory party and concerned with the needs

22:02.400 --> 22:10.160
of its constituents. And even worse than that, what was their success? Couldn't be tolerated.

22:10.720 --> 22:17.280
Yes, there are people in Cure Starmer's party who will object to what I'm saying, but I'm afraid

22:17.280 --> 22:24.480
it's the truth. When it comes to the next presidential election on your side of the Atlantic,

22:25.840 --> 22:30.880
can America cope with another four years of Trump or another four years of Biden?

22:32.560 --> 22:43.680
Well, the Republican Party really shouldn't be called a party anymore. I'd prefer the terms used by

22:43.680 --> 22:52.960
the political analysts of the conservative American Enterprise Institute who refer to it as a radical

22:52.960 --> 23:00.480
insurgency that has abandoned parliamentary politics. That's pretty accurate. If you look at

23:00.560 --> 23:08.080
international rankings of attitudes and so on, the Republican Party, if you want to call it that,

23:08.080 --> 23:16.320
ranks alongside the far-right parties in Europe with neo-fascist origins. And they've totally

23:16.320 --> 23:22.400
abandoned parliamentary politics. All you have to do is look at their programs. It's not even a joke.

23:23.360 --> 23:31.360
Program is block anything, anything that might harm profit and power of the very rich in the

23:31.360 --> 23:37.440
corporate sector. But right at the moment, sometimes it's almost comical, right at the moment,

23:38.400 --> 23:45.440
now that they've taken over the House, lead program, prevent the internal revenues

23:46.240 --> 23:54.240
service from checking tax cheats. That's their main program. Who are the tax cheats? Working people

23:54.240 --> 24:02.000
who file their income tax, rich and powerful, who have a battery of corporate lawyers who figure

24:02.000 --> 24:10.800
out a way not to pay taxes. The top program prevent the internet internally IRS from investigating

24:11.760 --> 24:20.800
them. Take a look at Trump's legislative programs. One achievement, a massive tax cut for the very

24:20.800 --> 24:30.400
rich in the corporate sector, stabbing everyone else in the back. Lead, a top issue for the

24:30.400 --> 24:39.120
Republican Party is don't touch the tax cut. The Biden administration came in with a

24:40.080 --> 24:45.440
moderately decent, not enough, but some kind of climate program. Actually,

24:46.240 --> 24:53.600
pretty significant advance over earlier ones, which is not saying much. Cut back point by point,

24:53.600 --> 25:03.840
step by step, by 100% Republican opposition. Not a single Republican would break ranks to say,

25:04.480 --> 25:10.480
let's do something about a climate problem which they know perfectly well has come and destroyed

25:11.360 --> 25:15.520
human civilization. Well, that's not a political party.

25:17.520 --> 25:24.960
You mentioned earlier in terms of social media and the bubbles and that we naturally end up in

25:24.960 --> 25:31.920
hearing more of what we already believe. Why can that not be weaponized by those who want change?

25:32.560 --> 25:38.640
Because you could argue either with unions and that there are ways of people online

25:39.200 --> 25:45.760
finding kindred spirits, lobbying, kind of building up power, or you could say in terms of

25:46.320 --> 25:52.000
challenging political parties around climate change. Why are those tools that are free and

25:52.000 --> 25:57.840
available not being weaponized by those who want to actually challenge those with power,

25:57.920 --> 26:03.760
those with corporate interests? Why is there not a grassroots revolution? What stops that?

26:06.480 --> 26:13.440
Well, it's not so easy to form a grassroots movement. You're against concentrated

26:15.120 --> 26:20.880
state and private power. When you try to do it, take a look at what happened to Corbyn.

26:21.840 --> 26:28.240
Take a look at what happened to the Republican Party when it started to veer slightly towards

26:28.880 --> 26:31.920
environment. Take a look at what's happened to the labor movement.

26:36.640 --> 26:41.040
Not for, in fact, you can ask yourself another question. Take a look at what happened. Take

26:41.040 --> 26:48.960
the United States, which is the leading in the lead in the neoliberal assault against the world,

26:48.960 --> 26:56.800
against the population. Well, there's measures of what's happened. The Miranda Corporation,

26:56.800 --> 27:03.280
very respectable quasi-governmental research corporation, did a study of the

27:04.960 --> 27:13.440
general economic effects of the neoliberal period. Over 40 years, they found,

27:13.440 --> 27:21.680
they studied what they called a lightly transfer of wealth, highway robbery to be more exact,

27:22.400 --> 27:29.840
transfer of wealth from the working class and the middle class, lower 90% of the population

27:30.400 --> 27:42.560
transferred to the top 1%, $50 trillion in 40 years. That's very effective class war.

27:43.440 --> 27:51.600
Well, you have concentrated economic power on one side, largely controlling the state. You have

27:52.240 --> 27:59.120
general population on the other side when there are efforts to make some moves. Concentrated power

28:00.240 --> 28:08.560
comes down on them very hard for the unions, Corbyn efforts, Sanders efforts, Lyman.

28:09.520 --> 28:19.520
You can fight against it. Over the centuries, there's been many victories. We don't have slavery.

28:20.080 --> 28:27.440
We don't have a few laws. There are victories, but they're hard to win. You have to recall,

28:27.440 --> 28:35.920
remember that those with, go back to Adam Smith at the beginning of the early days of the

28:36.880 --> 28:45.520
capitalist industrial revolution. I was an astute observer. He pointed out that in all ages,

28:46.640 --> 28:55.520
the masters of mankind pursue their vile maxim, all for ourselves, nothing for anyone else.

28:56.480 --> 29:02.800
Well, that was in the early stages. Now it's much more organized and controlled and so on,

29:02.800 --> 29:09.600
but the vile maxim still prevails, and you can see its consequences. You can fight against it.

29:10.320 --> 29:16.400
There have been victories, lots of victories even in recent years, but it's a struggle,

29:16.400 --> 29:21.120
and you're not going to win unless you recognize what the nature of the struggle is.

